{"author":{"id":"30a9cdd9e5369167dc36be4d3e5f98e516aa30b7571a17013bc815eef45f09c3"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445426017,"nonce":"2Ibp6MinNiZ4UG9ku4Q4MvHc2dE=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0OTg1ODE2Mw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/345#issuecomment-149858163"},"message":"@yhoogstrate \n\n\u003e It shouldn't be always running. Just the tabular file you have would be sufficient. Rather than using the sha256sum as uid you could use the url as a uid.\n\nURLs are not safe to use as filesystem names. There has to be a mapping between a requested URL and a path that nginx can understand. Either directly in the form of a sha256, or translated via a python script from URL -\u003e sha256 on disk.\n\n\u003e What I like about @bgruening's idea is that it requires PRs and some kind of checking before URLs get in the system.\n\nmy solution already covers that @yhoogstrate, the `urls.tsv` file will be part of the repository, people will PR that and we can have it be open/free for discussion.\n\n\u003e As long as the proxy server doesn't get hacked. The current implementation works like a 2-factor authentication because the checksums are not provided by the servers that host the packages (github excluded, but you get the point)\n\nThe only place where it matters that checksums are correct are on the end user's machine where the software is downloaded and installed. The proxy server and even upstream can have incorrect hashes associated with them as long as the end user's matches what is actually downloaded.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1445426497,"nonce":"j78lhGr1rN+ZOl8bXLd2PHGdeu8=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0OTg1OTQyMw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/345#issuecomment-149859423"},"message":"@bgruening \n\n\u003e @erasche this is great! Where is the code. \n\nIt wasn't online yet, pending discussion of the points I raised in an earlier comment, where should it go? I'll post in my personal github _pro tempore_. https://github.com/erasche/package-cache Here ya go. :)\n\n\u003e I'm wondering why we need a web-service at all, if we just want to map the packages to a URL.\n\nIt's no longer a web service, now just a directory full of tarballs that gets served. The only \"service\" aspect is the python script which downloads + mirrors tarballs as a cron job.\n\n\u003e This will download a package a ID augustus_3_1. The ID is unique and we can use it inside of download_by_url directly, if we implement something like https://github.com/bgruening/gsl/blob/master/gsl.py in Galaxy directly. We do not need to store the checksum inside of the tool_dependency as this script will take care of it. Not sure if github is happy with this usage, but essentially we do not need a server and can just collect and update all URLs in one place. But this makes it to a central point failure.\n\nYes, and more importantly it doesn't actually solve the problem of CPAN removing packages. That's the problem I'm trying to solve here. Your script could be part of this. I see no reason `gsl.py` wouldn't work with what I'm proposing. We can add an \"id\" column (or just rename the \"comment\" column) to that file and your gsl.py script to it, but we NEED to be hosting the tarballs.  \n\n\u003e That said, for the second problem I think we need to get founding for a download store to actually store the tarballs somewhere. My idea was to ask the ELIXIR project and especially the Sustainability Institute for help.\n\nEh, do we? That seems like a lot of work. The galaxy project is already hosting 200 gigs of R packages that no one will _ever_ want or access due to the way bioarchive works.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1445427380,"nonce":"aoJKdWPxekrChqK6As1hnayke7g=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0OTg2MTY5Mg==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/345#issuecomment-149861692"},"message":"@bgruening I've updated my repo with your GSL.py and implemented compatibility with it. The `urls.tsv` file now matches your `packages.list` (and displays more nicely on GH). \n\nWhenever we find a place to host these packages (I'm assuming Galaxy won't mind, failing that ELIXIR), we'll update the script with the new URL and it'll be 100% ready to go.","files":null}]}